    "contents" : "\\documentclass[10pt,a4paper]{article}\n\\usepackage[latin1]{inputenc}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\usepackage{amsfonts}\n\\usepackage{amssymb}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{hyperref}\n\\usepackage[round]{natbib}\n\n\\renewcommand{\\thesection}{\\arabic{section}.}\n\\numberwithin{equation}{section}\n\n\\renewcommand{\\theequation}{\\thesection\\arabic{equation}}\n\\renewcommand{\\thesubsection}{\\thesection\\arabic{subsection}}\n\n\\bibliographystyle{plainnat}\n\\author{Jonathan Sidi}\n\\title{Non Parametric Detection schemes and their Application to the Surveillance of Exponentially Tilted Joint Distributions}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\\maketitle\n\\begin{abstract}\nThis is the abstract\n\\end{abstract}\n\\begin{enumerate}\n\\item fit a model to each process\n\\item obtain residuals\n\\item fit copula to joint distribution of residuals\n\\end{enumerate}\n\nFitting Copulas\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\item symmetric copulas: Archemedian Copulas, ie the dependence between each set of variables is the same\n\\item Test fit using QQplot under Copula assumption\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\item Independent\n\\item Gumbel (Right Tail)\n\\item Clayton (Left Tail)\n\\end{itemize}\n\\item Can measure non-linear dependence\n\\item When measuring only two variables then symmetric copulas are good, but when there are more than 2 then there may be a problem because we are assuming all variables have the same dependence structure\n\\item In this case we need to move towards non-archemdian copulas, eg Gaussian or t.\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\item Gaussian is appealing since you only need the two marginals and one additional parameter - the correlation coefficient.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\section{Copulas}\nUsing the notation in \\cite{frees1998understanding} We consider $p$ uniform random variables $u_1,u_2,\\dots,u_p$, which are not assumed to be independent. Their relationship is defined as:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nC(u_1,u_2,\\dots,u_p)=P(U_1\\le u_1,U_2\\le u_2,\\dots,U_p\\le u_p),\n\\end{equation}\nwhere the function $C$ is called the copula. $U$ is a uniform random variable and $u$ is the realization. We then can select arbitrary marginal distribution functions $F_1(x_1),F_2(x_2),\\dots,F_p(x_p)$ and the function\n\n\\begin{equation}\nC(F_1(x_1),F_2(x_2),\\dots,F_p(x_p))=F(x_1,x_2,\\dots, x_p)\n\\end{equation}\ndefines the multivariate distribution at $x_1,x_2,\\dots, x_p$ with marginal distributions $F_1,F_2,\\dots, F_p$.\\\\\n\nsuppose $X \\sim F$, $Y \\sim G$ and $(X,Y) \\sim H$. Let $U\\equiv F(X)$ and $V\\equiv G(Y)$, where $U,V \\sim U(0,1)$ are the probability integral transforms of $X,Y$. let $(U,V) \\sim C$, we then obtain\n\n\\begin{eqnarray}\nc(F(X),G(Y))=&\th(X,Y)\\cdot \n\\begin{vmatrix}\ndX/dU&dX/dV\\\\\ndY/dU&dY/dV\n\\end{vmatrix}\\\\\n=&h(X,Y)\\cdot \n\\begin{vmatrix}\nf^{-1}(X)&0\\\\\n0&g^{-1}(Y)\n\\end{vmatrix} \\nonumber \\\\\n=&\\frac{h(X,Y)}{f(X)g(Y)} \\nonumber\n\\end{eqnarray}\n\nWe have now derived the joint density function $h(X,Y)$ as a function of the marginal and copula densities\n\n\\begin{equation}\nh(X,Y)=f(X)g(Y)c(F(X),G(Y)\n\\end{equation}\n\n\nUnder \\cite{sklar1959fonctions}: if the  marginal distributions are continuous, then there is a  unique copula  representation.\n\n\\begin{equation}\nH(x,y)=C(F(X),G(Y)) \\forall x,y \\in \\mathbb{R} \n\\end{equation}\n\n\\section{Time Dependent Copula}\nThe original copula theory was developed for the iid case, it can be extended to\n\\subsection{Bivariate}\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\item i.n.i.d\n\\begin{equation}\nH_t(x_t,y_t)=C(F(X_t),G(Y_t))\n\\end{equation}\n\\item d.n.i.d\n\\begin{equation}\nH_t(x_t,y_t|I_{t-1})=C(F(X_t),G(Y_t)|I_{t-1}),\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $I_t=\\sigma(z_{t+1},x_t,y_t,z_{t},x_{t-1},y_{t-1},\\dots)$\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{Vine Copula}\n\n\n\\section{Using Surveillance Techniques With Copulas}\nNow it is possible to try and capture the time-varying dependence by allowing the parameters of the copula to evolve over time. These parameters will be of interest in the SR and CUSUM.\n\n\\begin{table}[!h]\n\\centering\n\\caption{Surveillance Parameters in Copulas}\n\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}\n\\hline  Copula & Parameter \\\\ \n\\hline  Gaussian & $\\rho_t$ \\\\ \n\\hline  Joe-Clayton & $\\tau_t^L,\\tau_t^U$ \\\\ \n\\hline  &  \\\\ \n\\hline  &  \\\\ \n\\hline \n\\end{tabular} \n\\end{table}\n\n\n\n\\bibliography{copula}{}\n\n\n\n\n\\end{document}",
